docs.abstract: How a lawn sign inspired by mom décor became a liberal mantra — and a symbol of a political battle over white womanhood.
docs.snippet: How a lawn sign inspired by mom décor became a liberal mantra — and a symbol of a political battle over white womanhood.
docs.lead_paragraph: There is a sign that has become ubiquitous on the lawns of Democrats who have lawns. “In This House, We Believe,” the sign begins, followed by a stack of progressive maxims listed in capital letters. The classic version reads: “Black Lives Matter / Women’s Rights Are Human Rights / No Human Is Illegal / Science Is Real / Love Is Love.” Then the kicker: “Kindness Is Everything.”

headline.main: ‘In This House’ Yard Signs, and Their Curious Power
headline.print_headline: The Curious, Persistent Power  Of a Yard Sign That Went Viral

docs.abstract: The newly opened Museum at The Times, on the 15th floor of the Times Building in New York, is filled with curios and artifacts that date back 170 years.
docs.snippet: The newly opened Museum at The Times, on the 15th floor of the Times Building in New York, is filled with curios and artifacts that date back 170 years.
docs.lead_paragraph: On the 15th floor of The New York Times Building, near a newspaper that traveled close to 1.8 million miles aboard the space shuttle Columbia, is a slab of metal shaped as the letter “S.” It is a piece from the “zipper,” a belt of 14,800 bulbs that The New York Times operated to send news bulletins around Times Square, beginning in 1928.

headline.main: High Above the Newsroom, a History of The Times

docs.abstract: Here’s what we know about the emails from the former Las Vegas Raiders coach, and what happened after they came to light.
docs.snippet: Here’s what we know about the emails from the former Las Vegas Raiders coach, and what happened after they came to light.
docs.lead_paragraph: Jon Gruden resigned as the coach of the N.F.L.’s Las Vegas Raiders on Oct. 11 after The New York Times reported that he had made racist, homophobic and misogynistic remarks in numerous emails during a seven-year period ending in early 2018.

headline.print_headline: Gruden’s Emails and the Fallout: What We’ve Learned, and What Comes Next

docs.abstract: The enforcement methods of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police led a court to deny a logging company’s request to extend an injunction.

docs.lead_paragraph: This week, the Supreme Court of British Columbia refused to extend an injunction against old growth forest protests in and around Fairy Creek on Vancouver Island. But the rejection had nothing to do with logging or the actions of the protesters.

docs.abstract: Mr. McClain died days after he was detained by the police in Aurora in 2019. The terms of the settlement were not made public.
docs.snippet: Mr. McClain died days after he was detained by the police in Aurora in 2019. The terms of the settlement were not made public.
docs.lead_paragraph: The family of Elijah McClain, a 23-year-old Black man who died in 2019 after the police in Aurora, Colo., restrained him with a chokehold maneuver that has since been banned, has reached a settlement with the city, an official and lawyers for his parents said on Tuesday.

headline.main: Elijah McClain’s Family Reaches Settlement With City of Aurora, Colo.

docs.abstract: The unsigned decisions, without noted dissents, indicated that the court continued to support the widely criticized doctrine of qualified immunity.
docs.snippet: The unsigned decisions, without noted dissents, indicated that the court continued to support the widely criticized doctrine of qualified immunity.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In two unsigned decisions without noted dissents, the Supreme Court on Monday ruled in favor of police officers accused of using excessive force. The rulings were a signal that the court continues to support the doctrine of qualified immunity, which can shield police misconduct from lawsuits seeking damages.

headline.main: In Two Rulings, Supreme Court Bolsters Legal Shield for Police
headline.print_headline: Legal Shield For Officers Is Bolstered In 2 Decisions
